The newly installed Institute of Chartered Accountant of Nigeria (ICAN) President, Mr Nnamdi Okwuadigbo has vowed to deal with corruption among members. He said in other parts of the world, said institute to lead the crusade for transparency and accountability in governance. He said this in his acceptance speech shortly after he was installed as the 55th President of the institute by the immediate past President, Alhaji Razak Jaiyeola and the Registrar, Mr John Evbodaghe. “As a professional institute, we will continue to offer constructive advice to all tiers of government in our efforts to promote the culture of professionalism in the management of public resources, thereby facilitating the process of economic growth and development,” he noted. Okwuadigbo explained that as part of his plans, the Institute would seek the collaboration of accredited universities both to enhance the quality of their training curricula as well as an offer of a unique degree programme for chartered accountants, especially for Accounting Technicians. In his valedictory speech, Jaiyeola who spoke of his achievements in the last 12 months said, “We also introduced Teleconferencing/e-meeting solution across the three office locations in Victoria Island, Ebute-Metta and Abuja. The facility has provision for mobility and remote sign-on. It also makes management of meetings flexible and cost efficient.”  ICPC, CIBN to tackle corruption in financial sector Tough times await architects – ICPC promises Pro-Buhari rally holds in Kano Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin